# SprintAgent — Cursor Rules

## Agent Behavior
- Always generate STRICT valid JSON output
- Never include explanations, markdown, or extra text outside JSON
- Follow schema EXACTLY — no additional or missing fields

## Output Contract
Agent MUST return JSON with keys:
- feature_summary
- total_story_points
- tasks
- sprint_recommendation
- unknowns

Each task MUST contain:
- id
- title
- description
- story_points
- depends_on
- type (backend | frontend | infra | test | docs)
- code_stub
- risks
- acceptance_criteria

## Schema Enforcement
- Field names must NEVER change
- Missing fields are NOT allowed
- Extra fields are NOT allowed
- tasks must always be a list of objects

## Story Points Rules
- Use Fibonacci sequence: 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13
- No task may exceed 13 story points
- total_story_points MUST equal sum(tasks.story_points)

## Code Generation Rules
- All code MUST be valid Python
- Include:
  - Type hints
  - Google-style docstrings
  - TODO comments
  - Basic implementation structure (not just pass)
- No secrets or API keys in code

## Risk Guidelines
- Risks must be specific technical failure scenarios
- Avoid vague statements like "performance issues"
- Prefer:
  - race conditions
  - DB transaction failures
  - cache inconsistency
  - API timeout issues

## Acceptance Criteria
- Must be measurable and testable
- Include:
  - API endpoints
  - expected responses
  - status codes
  - input/output format

## Reliability Rules
- If JSON is invalid → trigger retry
- If schema mismatch → regenerate output
- Always prioritize correctness over creativity

## Evaluation Alignment
Agent output must maximize:
- task_quality
- code_quality
- planning_accuracy
- response_speed
- json_reliability

## Code Style
- Functions under 40 lines
- Type hints required
- Google-style docstrings
- Modular design preferred
- Never use os.environ directly — use load_dotenv()

## Workflow
- After changing SYSTEM_PROMPT → run:
  python main.py --benchmark

- After changing evaluator.py → run:
  python -m pytest tests/

## Security
- Never commit .env
- Never expose API keys
- Always use environment variables

## Strict Prohibitions
- No hardcoded secrets
- No schema deviation
- No unstructured output